1186–Deceased","1190–Female":"1190–Deceased","1210–Male":"1210–Deceased","1212–Female":"1212–Deceased","1214–Male":"1214–Deceased","1160–Male":"1160–Deceased","1165–Female":"1165–Deceased","1190":"1190","about 1184":"about 1184","1214":"1214","1212":"1212","1210":"1210","1165":"1165","1186":"1186","1209":"1209","1160":"1160","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Walcot, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Walcot, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Hereford, Herefordshire, England":"Hereford, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom","Weobley Castle, Herefordshire, England":"Weobley, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Marbury","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["habitational name from Marbury in Great Budworth, or, perhaps, from Marbury cum Quoisley (both in Cheshire). Both placenames derive from Old English <i>mere</i> ‘pool, lake’ + <i>burh</i> ‘fortress’ (dative <i>byrig</i>), ‘stronghold by the lake’.","variant of <b>Marbrow</b>, itself a variant of <b>Marlborough</b>, a habitational name from Marlborough (Wiltshire), which probably derives from an Old English personal name <i>Mǣrla</i> + Old English <i>beorg</i> ‘hill, mound’.","English:"],"variants":[{"name":"Marbry","meanings":["English: variant of   Marbury  ."]},{"name":"Marberry","meanings":["Altered form of English   Marbury  ."]}]},{"name":"Laurence","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a French form of Latin <i>Laurentius</i> ‘man from Laurentum’. <i>Laurentum</i> was a town in Latium, which may have got its name from Latin <i>laurus</i> ‘laurel’, although it is more probably of pre-Roman origin. The given name was moderately popular in the Middle Ages (when it was used for girls as well as boys), under the influence of a 3rd-century saint who was one of the seven deacons of Rome. He was martyred in  258 . The legend is that, having been required to hand over the Church's treasures to the civil authorities, he assembled the poor and sick and presented them. For this act of Christian defiance, he was roasted to death on a gridiron. In England the name is also associated with  St Laurence of Canterbury  (  d. 619 ). A more recent influence has been the actor  Sir Laurence Olivier  (  1907–89 ).  See also  Lawrence ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Laurence de Marbury was born in 1186, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, William De Marbury, was 26 and his mother, Mrs William De Marbury, was 22. He married Mazeline Laurence in 1209, in Hereford, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1186–":"1186–Surnud","1186–Male":"1186–Surnud","1190–Female":"1190–Surnud","1210–Male":"1210–Surnud","1212–Female":"1212–Surnud","1214–Male":"1214–Surnud","1160–Male":"1160–Surnud","1165–Female":"1165–Surnud","1190":"1190","about 1184":"umbes 1184","1214":"1214","1212":"1212","1210":"1210","1165":"1165","1186":"1186","1209":"1209","1160":"1160","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Walcot, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom